@node "Problem" "RealTime/Problem"
@next "Solution"
@prev "Main"
                             @{fg fill}RealTime 1.2@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

@{u}Problem@{uu}:-

The problem I had when I first got my amiga was a lack of time. Not a lack
of time to use it, but when I did use it, it never had the correct date and
time set in it.  When I bought my first 1/2 meg upgrade board for my A500,
then I was set, because along with that whole 1/2 meg came a battery backed
up clock!  But since I've upgraded to an Amiga 1200, I miss having the
correct time, especially when writing letters, e-mail, etc.  So I needed
Real Time.
@endnode

@node "Solution" "RealTime/Solution"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Problem"
                             @{fg fill}RealTime 1.2@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

@{u}Solution@{uu}:-

Well here's the solution to all your problems.  RealTime is a program
similar to the Time preferences found on Workbench 2 and above.  Some of you
may have noticed that, unlike most of the prefs programs, the Time program
does not save out a file when you click on Save, instead it attempts to
write the time to a battery backed up clock.  Well think how useful it would
be if it saved the time to a preferences file, then you could put Time into
the WBStartup drawer and set the correct time and date every time you boot.
Well now you can, since RealTime's save button saves the time to a file you
specify, then attempts to read it back from that file the next time it's
run.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "RealTime/Usage"
@next "Other"
@prev "Solution"
                             @{fg fill}RealTime 1.2@{fg text}
                  © 1996 Brain Destruction Software
                          Written by Burnsy

@{u}Usage@{uu}:-

RealTime can be run from the CLI or from Workbench, from either accepts two
optional arguments...

@{i}RealTime FROM,PUBSCREEN/K@{b}@{ui}

ToolTypes@{ub}:        @{i} PUBSCREEN
                   DATEFILE@{ui}

The first argument, @{i}FROM@{ui} or @{i}DATEFILE@{ui}, is the name of the file you wish to
store the date in, if this is ommited then RealTime will use the default
file S:Date.  The second argument @{i}PUBSCREEN@{ui} tells RealTime the name of the
Public Screen you wish it to open on, if this argument is ommited then it
will open on the Workbench screen.

Once the program is run.  It opens a window with four slider gadgets, these
control (from top to bottom) the Hours, the Minutes, the Months and the
Days.  There is also a display which shows the date selected, and a string
gadget to change the year.  Along the bottom are three buttons, Save, Use
and Cancel.  Use simply sets the current time/date as the time selected,
Save sets the time and saves the time to the file, and cancel quits the
program with no changes, as does the close gadget.  If the right mouse
button is pressed then an about window appears.
@endnode

